RQ 6.7.2: Suppression Effect Analysis
======================================================================

Loaded person-level data: 100 participants
======================================================================
PAIRWISE CORRELATIONS (Person-Level, N=100)
======================================================================

Variables:
  X = SD_confidence (confidence variability)
  Y = SD_accuracy (accuracy variability)
  Z = mean_accuracy (covariate / potential suppressor)

Correlations:
  r(X, Y) = -0.0146, p = 0.8851  [Target: SD_conf vs SD_acc]
  r(X, Z) = 0.2882, p = 0.0036  [SD_conf vs mean_acc]
  r(Y, Z) = -0.6119, p = 0.0000  [SD_acc vs mean_acc]

======================================================================
PARTIAL CORRELATION DECOMPOSITION
======================================================================

Formula: r(X,Y|Z) = [r(X,Y) - r(X,Z)*r(Y,Z)] / sqrt[(1-r(X,Z)²)(1-r(Y,Z)²)]

Numerator: r_xy - r_xz*r_yz = -0.0146 - (0.2882)*(-0.6119) = 0.1617
Denominator: sqrt[(1-0.2882²)(1--0.6119²)] = 0.7574
Partial r(X,Y|Z) = 0.2135

======================================================================
SUPPRESSION EFFECT ANALYSIS
======================================================================

SUPPRESSION DETECTED:
  |Partial r| (0.2135) > |Zero-order r| (0.0146)

INTERPRETATION:

  1. WHAT HAPPENED:
     - Zero-order correlation r(SD_conf, SD_acc) = -0.0146 (NULL)
     - BUT controlling for mean accuracy reveals r_partial = 0.2135 (SIGNIFICANT)

  2. WHY (SUPPRESSION MECHANISM):
     - SD_confidence and mean_accuracy are positively correlated (r = 0.2882)
     - SD_accuracy and mean_accuracy are negatively correlated (r = -0.6119)

  3. MATHEMATICAL EXPLANATION:
     - Binary SD_accuracy is constrained: SD = sqrt[p*(1-p)]
     - This constraint creates NEGATIVE r(SD_acc, mean_acc) near extremes
     - r(SD_acc, mean_acc) = -0.6119

     - Meanwhile, high-ability participants have CONSISTENT confidence
     - r(SD_conf, mean_acc) = 0.2882

     - These opposing paths CANCEL OUT in zero-order correlation
     - Removing mean_accuracy reveals the TRUE metacognitive relationship

======================================================================
THEORETICAL INTERPRETATION
======================================================================

FINDING: After controlling for ability (mean accuracy):
  - Partial r = 0.2135, p < .05
  - Within ability levels, people with variable confidence also have variable accuracy

IMPLICATION:
  - Metacognitive variability DOES track encoding variability
  - BUT this relationship is MASKED by ability-related confounds
  - People with similar ability show correlated confidence-accuracy variability

THESIS SIGNIFICANCE:
  - Supports metacognitive monitoring hypothesis (confidence tracks memory state)
  - But zero-order null means variability relationship only emerges within ability bands
  - This is a PARTIAL SUPPORT finding, not full support

